# Agent memory

Cross-session lessons live in the `memory` skill. Adding an entry regenerates the skill.

## When to read

Read the `memory` skill before similar work, when you hit a recurring issue, or when the user asks what has been learned.

## How to read

1. Read `~/.agents/skills/memory/SKILL.md`.
2. For entries whose id is a link, also read `~/.agents/skills/memory/references/<id>.md`.

## When to add

Add only when the lesson would save time next session:

- Recurring pitfall or non-obvious convention
- Fix that took real investigation

Skip one-off task notes, obvious facts, or topics already covered. Read the skill first - duplicate ids are rejected.

## How to add

```bash
memory add <kebab-id> "<one sentence, max 120 chars>"
memory add <kebab-id> "<one sentence>" --detail "<root cause, fix, why it wasn't obvious>"
```

- `<kebab-id>`: lowercase letters, digits, hyphens only
- Sentence: single line, 120 chars max. Quote it if the shell would split it
- Use `--detail` for anything that does not fit in the one-liner

### Examples

```bash
# Good: non-obvious, reusable
memory add stow-symlink "dotfiles stow skips targets that already exist as real files"

# Skip: one-off, no cross-session value
memory add fixed-typo "fixed a typo in README"
```
